## A community is a group of individuals of *different* [[Unsorted/Species\|species]] that occupy a specific area at the same time

- Focuses on interactions between both members of different species and members of the same species

## Interactions within communities:
- 2 primary types:

### Int*ra*specific interactions
- Interactions between [[Unsorted/Populations\|members of the same species]]
- **Competition** for:
	- The *resources* necessary for their [[Unsorted/Niches\|niche]]
	- Mates


### Int*er*specific interactions
- Interactions between members of *different* species
- 6 primary types:



#### Mutualism (++)
- Mutually-beneficial interactions between species
- IE [[Unsorted/Humans\|humans]] and crops

#### Commensalism (+o)
- When one species benefits but the other is unaffected
- Fairly intimate, can be a primary food source for the species that benefits
- Examples
	- Cleaner fish
	- birds waiting for bugs to be exposed by cattle grazing
	- Epiphytes growing on trees, trees are unharmed



#### Predation (+-)
- When one organism consumes the other
- Leads to adaptations which help hunt or avoid hunting
	- Predator adaptations
		- Snakes can see infrared heat emissions
		- Sharks have electroceceptors
	- Prey adaptations
		- Passive defenses:
			- Hiding
				- Burrowing
				- Camoflauge
					- Geckos and octopi modifying their color and textures
					- Bright warning coloration in dangerous prey
					- Mimicry of dangerous prey patterns to appear dangerous
			- Spikes, horns, etc in both herbivores and plants
		- Active defenses:
			- fleeing/defending self and offspring
			- Mobbing against predators
			- Distracting the predators to redirect them
				- Killdeer birds will play dead and flail to distract predators that get too close to their nests 



#### Parasitism (+-)
- More intimate than predation
- Benefits one, harms the other
	- Unlike predation, parasites often avoid killing the host, as that typically would result in their death as well



#### Amensalism (o-)
- When one organism is harmed but the other is unaffected
- Incidental harm, like inedible plants and insects being trampled by grazers



#### Competition (--)
- Competition is the relationship that occurs when multiple organisms seek the same limited resources, or [[Unsorted/Niches\|niche]]
	- Both organisms are harmed
	- Can happen on the level of [[Unsorted/Individual organisms\|Individual organisms]], [[Unsorted/Species\|Species]], and even [[Unsorted/Populations\|Populations]]
	- They can't coexist indefinitely
		- One will eventually be pushed out because the other is better suited to the [[Unsorted/Niches\|niche]]
			- This creates significant pressure for the loser to seek alternative sources of essential resources, and a new [[niche\|niche]]
			- Though it often results in death when other suitable niches are also occupied
- Can also occur within [[Unsorted/Populations\|Populations]]
